    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effect of using Psidium ramboanum are inducing nausea due to its high concentration of compounds like psidium alkaloids and flavonoids, which can cause stomach discomfort and vomiting in some individuals. This improper use can also lead to diarrhea, as the plant's high fiber content can irritate the digestive system and cause water loss. Furthermore, skin irritation may occur due to the presence of irritant compounds like saponins and tannins, which can cause redness, itching, and blistering. In addition, Psidium ramboanum may exacerbate allergies in people who are sensitive to plant-based allergens, leading to symptoms like hives, itching, and swelling. These side effects are likely due to the plant's high concentration of bioactive compounds, which can have unpredictable effects when used improperly.",
    "uses": "Psidium ramboanum is a species of plant that has been reported to have various medicinal properties. The leaves and fruits of the plant are used in traditional medicine to treat several health conditions. Psidium ramboanum has been used to treat digestive issues, such as diarrhea and dysentery, due to its anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. The plant also has antioxidant and anti-hemorrhagic properties, which make it useful in treating wounds and preventing excessive bleeding. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of Psidium ramboanum as a medicinal plant.",
    "taxonomy": "Psidium ramboanum is a species of flowering plant in the family Myrtaceae. It is native to the island of Madagascar and is part of the genus Psidium, which includes guavas. Within the Myrtaceae family, Psidium ramboanum is classified as a member of the tribe Myrteae. The classification of Psidium ramboanum at the genus and family level is well established, but further specific classification at the subfamily or other levels is less documented. More research is needed to fully understand the classification of this species within the Myrtaceae family.",
    "benefits": "Psidium ramboanum is a species of guava native to Brazil, and it has been reported to have potential health benefits. Its leaves are rich in antioxidants and flavonoids, which may help protect against cell damage and inflammation. The fruit of Psidium ramboanum is also rich in vitamins and minerals, including vitamin C and potassium, making it a nutritious addition to a healthy diet. The plant's anti-inflammatory properties may also help to reduce the risk of chronic diseases, such as heart disease and diabetes. Further research is needed to fully understand the health benefits of Psidium ramboanum.",
    "parts": "Psidium ramboanum, a species of guava, is known to have various medicinal properties. The leaves and fruits of this plant are primarily used in traditional medicine. The leaves are used to treat various health issues, including fever, cold, and skin infections, due to their antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties. The fruits are rich in vitamins and antioxidants, and are used to treat digestive problems and reduce inflammation. Further research is needed to fully explore the medicinal potential of Psidium ramboanum.",
    "intro": "Psidium ramboanum, commonly known as the Rambo guava, is a species of flowering plant in the family Myrtaceae, native to the Amazon rainforest. The Rambo guava has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, exhibiting health benefits such as anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and antimicrobial activities, which may help alleviate symptoms of digestive issues and skin infections. Bioactive constituents of Psidium ramboanum include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and tannins, which are responsible for its therapeutic properties. The Rambo guava is often used to prepare herbal teas, infusions, and decoctions, as well as being incorporated into traditional remedies and supplements."
